Fifeshire, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom","Balgregie, Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Melville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from any of the various places in Normandy called Malleville, from Latin <i>mala</i> ‘bad’ + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’.","Irish (mainly Ulster): English surname adopted by bearers of Gaelic <b>Ó Maoilmhichíl</b> ‘descendant of <i>Maoilmhichil</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘devotee of (Saint) Michael’.","History: The American novelist Herman Melville (1819–91) was a descendantof the Scottish Melvilles. His maternal grandfather was the revolutionary war general Peter Gansevoort (born 1749 in Albany, NY). His paternal grandfather was Maj. Thomas Melville of Boston. Irish bearers of the name claim descent from Maol Mhichíl, a chief of Síol Muireadhaigh (County Roscommon) in the 9th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Melvin","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): variant of   Melville   with alternation of final <i>-l</i> and <i>-n</i>.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Maoil Mhín</b> ‘descendant of the devotee of Maoilmhín’, a personal name meaning ‘gentle chieftain’."]},{"name":"Mulville","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Melville  ."]},{"name":"Mellin","meanings":["Scottish (Glamorgan): variant of   Melville  .","German: habitational name from any of various places so called.","English: variant of   Melling  ."]},{"name":"Mulvihill","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Paddy.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Maoil Mhichíl</b> ‘descendant of the devotee of (Saint) Michael’. The Anglicized form was sometimes abbreviated into   Melville  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Margaret Melville of Cairnbee was born in 1354, in Ross-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, Robert Melville de Cairnbee, was 25 and her mother, Lady Melville Of Carnbrie, was 26. She married John De Boswell - Second Lord of Balgregie in 1367, in Fife, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1354–":"1354–Surnud","1354–Female":"1354–Surnud","1347–1395":"1347–1395","1365–1395":"1365–1395","1372–1429":"1372–1429","1382–Male":"1382–Surnud","1329–Male":"1329–Surnud","1329–Female":"1329–Surnud","1347":"1347","1367":"1367","1354":"1354","1365":"1365","1395":"1395","about 1365":"umbes 1365","1 January 1372":"1. jaanuar 1372","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1429":"1429","1329":"1329","Balmuto, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Cairnbee, Ross, Ross and Cromarty, Scotland":"Ross-shire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Balgregie, Fifeshire, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Balgregie, Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland"},"fi":{"1354–":"1354–Kuollut","1354–Female":"1354–Kuollut","1347–1395":"1347–1395","1365–1395":"1365–1395","1372–1429":"1372–1429","1382–Male":"1382–Kuollut","1329–Male":"1329–Kuollut","1329–Female":"1329–Kuollut","1347":"1347","1367":"1367","1354":"1354","1365":"1365","1395":"1395","about 1365":"noin 1365","1 January 1372":"1. tammikuuta 1372","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1429":"1429","1329":"1329","Balmuto, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Fife, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cairnbee, Ross, Ross and Cromarty, Scotland":"Ross-shire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Balgregie, Fifeshire, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Balgregie, Fife, Scotland":